e short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American short story writers]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:Novelists from New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Screenwriters from New Mexico]]\n[[Category:American male bloggers]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_R._R._Martin"}
{"title_page": "Mike Amodeo", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2014}}\n{{Infobox ice hockey player\n| name = Mike Amodeo\n| image = \n| caption =\n| image_size = 225px\n| played_for = '''''[[National Hockey League|NHL]]'''''<br>[[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|Winnipeg Jets]]<br>'''''[[World Hockey Association|WHA]]'''''<br>[[Ottawa Nationals]]<br>[[Toronto Toros]]<br>[[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|Winnipeg Jets]]<br>'''''[[American Hockey League|AHL]]'''''<br>[[Rochester Americans]]<br>'''''[[Central Professional Hockey League|CHL]]'''''<br>[[Tulsa Oilers (1964\u201384)|Tulsa Oilers]]<br>'''''[[Swedish Hockey League|SEL]]'''''<br>[[\u00d6rebro IK]]\n| ntl_team = Italy\n| position = [[Defenceman|Defence]]\n| shoots = Left\n| height_ft = 5\n| height_in = 10\n| weight_lb = 190\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1952|06|22}}\n| birth_place = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], Canada\n| draft = 102nd overall\n| draft_year = 1972\n| draft_team = [[California Golden Seals]]\n| wha_draft = \n| wha_draft_year = \n| wha_draft_team = \n| career_start = 1972\n| career_end = 1983\n}}\n'''Michael Anthony Amodeo''' (born June 22, 1952) is a retired professional [[ice hockey]] player who played 300 games in the [[World Hockey Association]] and 19 games in the [[National Hockey League]]. He played for the [[Ottawa Nationals]], [[Toronto Toros]], and [[Winnipeg Jets (1972\u201396)|Winnipeg Jets]]. As a youth, he played in the 1965 [[Quebec International Pee-Wee Hockey Tournament]] with the Scarboro Lions [[minor ice hockey]] team.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.publicationsports.com/ressources/files/439/Joueurs_Pro.pdf|title=Pee-Wee players who have reached NHL or WHA|year=2018|website=Quebec International Pee-Wee Hockey Tournament|access-date=2019-01-04}}</ref> Also he finished his career in Europe playing in Sweden and Italy.  \n\n==Career statistics==\n{| border=\"0\" cellpadding=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"text-align:center; width:60em\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\" \n! colspan=\"3\